Solution:\n    def secondsToRemoveOccurrences(self, s: str) -> int:\n        seconds = 0\n        while \"01\" in s:\n            s = s.replace(\"01\", \"10\")\n            seconds += 1\n        return seconds\n```\n\nThis solution works by repeatedly replacing all occurrences of \"01\" with \"10\" in the string `s` until there are no more \"01\" substrings left. It counts the number of replacements (seconds) needed to achieve this state and returns that count.\n\nTo address the follow-up question, the above solution is not O(n) due to the repeated scanning and replacing of the string. To achieve O(n) time complexity, we can use a different approach that avoids repeatedly scanning the entire string:\n\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def secondsToRemoveOccurrences(self, s: str) -> int:\n        seconds = 0\n        zeros = 0\n        for i, char in enumerate(s):\n            if char == '0':\n                zeros += 1\n            elif zeros > 0:\n                seconds = max(seconds + 1, zeros)\n        return seconds\n```\n\nThis optimized solution iterates through the string once, keeping track of the number of '0's encountered (`zeros`). When it encounters a '1', it updates the `seconds` to be the maximum of its current value plus one or the number of '0's seen so far. This ensures that the maximum number of seconds required to move all '0's to the left of all '1's is calculated in a single pass.", "estimated_date": 1660435200000}